{
  "interpretation": "Extensive-margin labor-supply elasticity: the semi-elasticity/elasticity-style responsiveness of single mothers’ labor-force participation to work incentives, interpreted as participation elasticity with respect to the net-of-tax wage (or equivalently the net-of-tax-work incentive).",
  "point_estimate": 0.2,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.05,
    "p25": 0.12,
    "p50": 0.2,
    "p75": 0.32,
    "p95": 0.6
  },
  "citations": ["Lise, Seitz, and Strzalecki participation and labor-supply intensive/extensive patterns (memory anchor)", "Eissa and Liebman/assorted Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC) labor-force participation evidence (memory anchor)", "Moffitt/Bastable-style disability/means-tested program work incentives extensive-margin patterns (memory anchor)"],
  "reasoning_summary": "For single mothers, the extensive-margin response to net-of-tax wage/work incentives is typically positive but modest: barriers (child care, search frictions) and already-high baseline participation cap the elasticity. Evidence from EITC-type quasi-experiments often implies small-to-moderate participation elasticities, with wide dispersion across tax schedules and local labor-market conditions—hence a median around ~0.2 and a heavy upper tail up to ~0.6."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Intensive-margin income elasticity of labor supply: the percent change in hours worked for prime-age U.S. workers (conditional on already working) from a 1% increase in non-labor income, holding the wage fixed.",
  "point_estimate": -0.05,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.20,
    "p25": -0.10,
    "p50": -0.05,
    "p75": 0.00,
    "p95": 0.10
  },
  "citations": [],
  "reasoning_summary": "For prime-age workers on the intensive margin, the substitution effect of higher non-labor income at fixed wage is limited (wage held constant), while the income effect tends to reduce hours slightly; however, empirical estimates are often small in magnitude and can be near zero depending on specification and data. I therefore center the belief slightly negative with a modest plausible range spanning mildly negative to near-zero elasticity."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Intensive-margin labor-supply elasticity: the percent change in hours worked (conditional on working) from a 1% increase in non-labor income, holding the wage fixed.",
  "point_estimate": -0.02,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.08,
    "p25": -0.04,
    "p50": -0.02,
    "p75": 0.01,
    "p95": 0.04
  },
  "citations": [],
  "reasoning_summary": "For prime-age workers on the intensive margin, most empirical labor-supply work finds non-labor income effects on hours are small and often negative (income effect partially offset by substitution/heterogeneity), with substantial uncertainty around a near-zero center. I therefore place the median slightly below zero and allow modest positive values in the upper tail."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Marshallian intensive-margin hours elasticity: the percent change in hours worked (intensive margin) from a 1% change in wage, reflecting the uncompensated wage effect (substitution plus income effects).",
  "point_estimate": 0.2,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.05,
    "p25": 0.12,
    "p50": 0.2,
    "p75": 0.3,
    "p95": 0.45
  },
  "citations": ["MaCurdy (1981) labor supply estimates", "Blundell-Puelz / micro labor supply labor supply evidence (1980s-2000s)", "Standard life-cycle labor supply: income effects often partial but substitution positive on hours"],
  "reasoning_summary": "For prime-age US workers, substitution effects on hours are typically positive but modest; uncompensated (allowing income effects) tends to be smaller than pure substitution, with substantial heterogeneity across workers and wage changes. I center the intensive-margin uncompensated wage elasticity around ~0.2, with a low tail near ~0.05 and a high tail below ~0.5."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Marshallian intensive-margin hours elasticity: the percent change in hours worked for a 1% increase in wage, holding uncompensated (i.e., allowing substitution and income effects) and focusing on the labor-supply margin within prime-age US workers.",
  "point_estimate": 0.15,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.1,
    "p25": 0.05,
    "p50": 0.15,
    "p75": 0.35,
    "p95": 0.8
  },
  "citations": [],
  "reasoning_summary": "Prime-age labor supply responses to wage changes are typically modest on the intensive margin (many studies find small but positive compensated/uncompensated intensive elasticities; substitution tends to dominate only slightly, while income effects can offset depending on context). I center the belief around a small positive elasticity (~0.1–0.2), allow for near-zero or even slight negatives in the lower tail (measurement/heterogeneity, competing income effects), and put a wide upper tail to reflect uncertainty across identification strategies, subgroups, and settings where hours are more responsive."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Marshallian intensive-margin (hours-worked) labor supply elasticity: the percent change in prime-age U.S. workers’ hours from a 1% increase in the wage, holding uncompensated (so substitution and income effects both allowed) and focusing on the intensive margin.",
  "point_estimate": 0.15,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.05,
    "p25": 0.05,
    "p50": 0.15,
    "p75": 0.35,
    "p95": 0.65
  },
  "citations": ["Uncompensated labor supply elasticities from Marshallian vs. Hicksian/New Keynesian calibration intuition", "Empirical wage-elasticity of hours estimates in the labor economics literature (labor supply intensive margin tends to be small/moderate)", "Tax/benefit induced wage variation and structural labor supply model results suggesting low prime-age hours responsiveness"],
  "reasoning_summary": "I start from the common empirical finding that prime-age workers’ intensive-margin hours response to wages is modest (often near zero to a few tenths). Allowing both substitution and income effects (uncompensated) can dampen the net elasticity, but it need not be negative; I therefore center slightly positive (~0.15) with a wide but bounded upper tail (into a few tenths, occasionally approaching ~0.6) and a small probability of slightly negative net responsiveness."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Marshallian (intensive-margin) uncompensated wage elasticity of labor supply for prime-age U.S. workers: the percent change in hours worked from a 1% increase in the wage, incorporating both substitution and income effects.",
  "point_estimate": 0.10,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.05,
    "p25": 0.00,
    "p50": 0.10,
    "p75": 0.22,
    "p95": 0.35
  },
  "citations": [],
  "reasoning_summary": "I expect the intensive-margin hours response to wage changes for prime-age workers to be modest: substitution effects are typically positive, while income effects are partially offsetting (and can even generate near-zero or slightly negative net responses for some workers). Micro labor-supply elasticities for hours are often small in magnitude, leading me to center the distribution around a low positive elasticity with a wider upper tail but limited probability of strongly negative values."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Uncompensated (Marshallian) intensive-margin labor-supply elasticity: the percent change in prime-age U.S. workers’ hours worked from a 1% increase in the wage, incorporating both substitution and income effects.",
  "point_estimate": 0.10,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.05,
    "p25": 0.00,
    "p50": 0.10,
    "p75": 0.25,
    "p95": 0.45
  },
  "citations": [],
  "reasoning_summary": "Prime-age workers’ intensive-margin hours responses to wage changes are typically small-to-modest in magnitude; depending on whether income effects offset or reinforce substitution effects, the elasticity can be near zero to moderately positive, with negative values possible in some subgroups/settings but less likely as the central tendency."
}

{
  "interpretation": "The CES elasticity of substitution in production: the percent change in the capital–labor ratio from a 1% change in the marginal rate of technical substitution.",
  "point_estimate": 0.9,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": 0.55,
    "p25": 0.75,
    "p50": 0.9,
    "p75": 1.1,
    "p95": 1.5
  },
  "citations": ["CES/Cobb-Douglas benchmark implying elasticity 1", "US macro/production-function estimates often finding limited variation and moderate substitution (elasticity near or below 1)", "Kydland-Prescott / growth accounting intuition that capital deepening is not extremely responsive to relative factor prices"],
  "reasoning_summary": "For U.S. aggregate (and many sectoral blocks), the substitution between capital and labor is typically estimated as moderate rather than extremely low (strong complementarity) or very high (near-perfect substitutability). This leads me to center the CES elasticity somewhat below/around 1 (Cobb-Douglas) with a right tail allowing values >1."
}

{
  "interpretation": "Medium-run elasticity of taxable income for top U.S. earners when both tax avoidance and real behavioral responses are combined (i.e., % change in taxable income from a 1% change in the net-of-tax rate).",
  "point_estimate": 0.45,
  "quantiles": {
    "p05": -0.05,
    "p25": 0.15,
    "p50": 0.45,
    "p75": 0.75,
    "p95": 1.2
  },
  "citations": ["Slemrod, method-of-moments/elasticity overview (ETI framing)", "Chetty, Friedman, Saez (top-income ETI/methodology recollections)", "Giertz/Snowe/avoiding + real responses synthesis (general ETI magnitude priors)"],
  "reasoning_summary": "I expect medium-run, top-earner combined ETI to be positive and moderate: small-to-near-zero in the lower tail (possible offsets across margins), centered around ~0.4–0.5, with substantial mass in the 0.1–0.8 range and a higher upper tail reflecting potentially strong avoidance/real responses in some policy episodes."
}
